Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament refused, as part of an amendment to the criminal law, the plan to cancel the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
The deputies refused at second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for concluding an apparently disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court must rule on the appeal of the condemned in December.
Tymosenko calls the judgment a political revenge for the regime and has sparked a process of suspicion of court bias also in the west.
The project to cancel paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the ex-Prime Minister was sentenced, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
