History of IBM: From slices of cheese to flights in the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it initially had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old &quot;time clocks&quot;, clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 chaired the company&#39;s Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of the firm - it is on Watson&#39;s ideas that the identity and culture of the company are based until now.
Watson ran the firm until 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
During Watson&#39;s first four years in office, revenues multiplied to $9 million and began the firm&#39;s expansion into all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM people and computers helped NASA guide flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile in 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC which determined the computer standard of the time with the name of IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with consulting and services with high added value.
The successful strategy at IBM over the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept &quot;a smarter planet&quot;.
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited such as transport and city management.
As far as commerce is concerned, IBM has recently developed a &quot;Smarter Commerce&quot; platform which helps salespeople manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in our territory.
It created its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is headquartered in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team dealing with speech recognition.
