How have travel prices evolved since 1989?
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips mostly to countries of the socialist bloc, as trips to the west were very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays to East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A big exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a western inclination and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however, you had to queue all night with a sleeping bag or else have a &quot;good knowledge&quot; within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency deal that was a condition for traveling west was denied to &quot;politically incorrect&quot; people who couldn&#39;t travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was however not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were consequently many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought for themselves and this habit lasts until now.
The travels of the Czechs have since experienced a great revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 vacations in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak, last year Czechs spent 4 million vacation days abroad in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90s of the last century in the western neighboring countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially to Austria, Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by plane to the west, which everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example in Paris the travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip in those days was to take your own tinned food, sausage, etc. with you to save money.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after decades to be able to freely buy western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary increased which caused around the year 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to a growing demand for trips, travel agencies have started since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter connections which, thanks to contracts, have reduced costs considerably compared to what there was before.
At the end of the 90s of the last century the Czechs had visa-free connections with practically most developed countries around the world apart from the USA which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations starting from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period which symbolizes our post-revolution development happened in 2008.
on November 17, 2008 the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to completely belong to the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008 Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad including additional charges. Crowns per person.
