The most beautiful swimming pools in Europe
A leap into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pools in UFO optics, magnificent pools of Budapest: Who travels through Europe can experience his blue miracle - and after touring the city or taking a long walk - can let his tired legs rest in sparkling water baths .
A book shows in which swimming pool one can experience the most well-being.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip for the past 18 months, there is one item that should not be missing in her luggage: her bathing suit.
Lying on her back in the water, she gazed at the artistically arranged domes, and swam against the Putten marbles that awaited her on the other side of the pool and admired the meticulously restored Art Nouveau of these converted pools.
If an indoor swimming pool pleased her, she immediately jotted down in her notebook all the details worthy of interest on the type of construction and on the history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools were surveyed in this way by the architectural historian Meder and she presented them in her already published book: &quot;Badefreuden (Joys of the Bath&quot;. The municipal indoor swimming pools of Munich, the historic bathing palaces in the black forest, &quot;Hardcore concrete buildings&quot; in the Taunus.
She has conducted her &quot;trips to the most exceptional baths of Central Europe&quot; in 13 countries. Besides Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, Czechia, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland and a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia respectively.
The 46-year-old German is a real fan of bathing culture.
Meder explains that she doesn&#39;t have much of an interest in the sport, but she finds herself drawn to the water in a totally different way.
It&#39;s irritating that swim fans have to settle for staring at blue tiles and put up with the stench of bleach while joggers breathe in the heady scent of spruce forests or can listen to the chirping of cheerful birds in the park.
“I once wondered why swimming pools must in fact always be so ugly,” said the Viennese.
&quot;So I was starting a collection of beautiful baths.&quot;
The surface of the water reinforces the architecture doubly
A dip in a swimming pool and the volatile sauna oils - the feel-good factor in the swimming halls are enormous because all the senses are awakened, according to Meder.
And if the builders had taken a little more trouble, the swimming rooms could be a real delight for the eyes: &quot;Instead of a floor, there is a surface of water in the swimming rooms.&quot;
&quot;It is on one side transparent, but on the other side however reflects the beauty of the entire building.&quot;
All the surfaces present themselves optically in a double way: high vaults, multicolored tiles, springboards.
The small-format image volume &quot;Badefreuden&quot; makes an interesting 190-page report on the architectural and cultural history of the historic wellness oasis - it certainly makes you want to jump into blue.
The collector Meder discovered remarkable examples during her research in Hungary.
Alongside splendid wellness baths like the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found nitrate-containing waters in a natural cave in the karst (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath whose basins are filled with water containing alkali and (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény) and located in a bottle-shaped building.
On the other hand, the heated outdoor swimming pools of Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views. While from a roof of the Zürich bath you have the whole city in view, you can admire the snow-capped Arlberg from an outdoor swimming pool in St. Anton: The Turkish bath has a window from which one can observe the animation on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits swimmers in Längenfeld: The Aqua Dome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed on the Alps.
In winter, steam rises from the three open plateaus, while in the background the Ötztal mountains rise skyward.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
the smell of bleach does not emanate from all swimming pools in the Meder collection.
Many thermal baths emanate the smell of sulfur, from the Árpád-spa in the Hungarian Bekescsaba emanates a strong smell of petroleum, which is hard to believe, being in a health spa.
The smell comes from the therapeutic alkaline waters containing carbon hydrogen which is almost black and its ooze sticks to your skin as soon as you drop into the pool - a special spa experience.
During her search for beautiful swimming pools, Iris Meder also suffered disappointments: When she wanted to visit Bad Luhatschowitz, a free outdoor swimming pool in Czechoslovakia, she found herself in front of a barricaded field.
The bath designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902 was closed in the meantime.
Glancing out the window of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she observed the weeds flourishing between the panes.
She observed the opposite effect in a charming pool in the Black Forest: The spa palace of Bad Wildbad.
This building has already survived three phases; you can discover not only neo-Roman elements that have emerged since its conception in 1844 but also a Moorish room in the Alhambra style which was added to it in 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the spa palace has remained the favorite bathing place of swimming pool expert Iris Meder - and not just because she is from Schwarzwald.
&quot;It&#39;s already a great achievement to fuse so many different construction styles into such a great unit,&quot; says Meder.
With such a palace, diving in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor matter.
