21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion that moved
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, was a museum in Vienna, stood empty and then fell into disrepair.
Now it is open again and serves as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about a modern post-war architecture, for its clear forms, its glass sheds, its lively and bold looks and its new building materials which are typical of the belief in technical progress, then Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer&#39;s pavilion for the 1958 Brussels World&#39;s Fair is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion once received the &quot;Grand Prix d&#39;Architecture&quot; for its steel and glass construction, light and suspended.
The construction is considered to this day as an important step in contemporary architecture.
He made architects so famous that he also built the Pavilion for the following Austrian World&#39;s Fair.
With its legendary four-cylinder house from BMW and its adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally rose to international fame in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the World&#39;s Fair in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the artworks on, so not a good environment.
However, it was also used for a long time, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building had been empty and increasingly dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name &quot;House of the 21st century&quot; and will in future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opened the first exhibition - a stroke of luck from every point of view.
The new beginning was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who in 2007 became the new director of the Austrian gallery Belvédère.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career, among other things in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby&#39;s, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she has carried out particularly well the work of transformation with politicians and the protection of monuments, it has obtained public funds and private sponsorship and has established its operation.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a café and a bookstore are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict monitoring, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal performer.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded Joseph Olbracht&#39;s secession and had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was &quot;a place extremely important&quot; place where he had seen &quot;virtually every weekend&quot; the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness following its move to Vienna and its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was &quot;an abyss in energy&quot;, says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was fitted and the roof replaced with special safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges have been reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled coverings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a dim light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it&#39;s almost new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in a red-brown rust protection tint.
And the movie theater is even exactly the same as it once was.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
&quot;Often good and inexpensive materials had to be found, which also appeal to the monument protection office&quot;, says Krischanitz and draws attention to a rough basement floor.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building has remained flexible and light.
It would have been difficult with the Pavilion, &quot;which came from Brussels,&quot; Krischanitz said recently, a typical &quot;Drop-in-the-City&quot; story.
Such architecture is &quot;always in the wrong place&quot; and still wants to &quot;awaken a clear conscience&quot;.
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a matter of a stroke of luck of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden rises precisely the &quot;quarter of the central station&quot; while newly planned, with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck may be coming: the House of the 21st Century could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the temporary art center in Berlin, and as it is said , it is already negotiating with the city to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
