In October 2008 disaster followed: UBS was, due to its investment mistakes, in financial crisis before bankruptcy and had to be rescued by the state.
The national bank bought tens of billions of problematic securities from UBS, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for bonds convertible into shares, for which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shaken - as it noted how dramatic it can be for a small country to house such large banks.
Finally, the balance sheet total of UBS in 2007 amounted to more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see graph).
&quot;We couldn&#39;t save UBS again,&quot; says bank researcher Geiger.
After the first disaster, the second followed.
Already a few months before, UBS had capitulated because of a tax dispute with America and declared itself ready to publish the data of wealthy clients, who had evaded taxes perhaps with the help of the Bank.
In addition, she accepted a payment of 780 million dollars - in reimbursement of unjustified profits from these operations with an increased fine.
So UBS has more or less published that it has assisted in tax evasion.
At the same time she lost something that has always been her capital in competition with wealthy clients: the prestige of discretion.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the removal of the head of the board of directors and the chairman of the board of directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Thus the bank had lost in a few months its credibility in the two main sectors of business: the banking investment because of bad speculations and the management of assets because of the aid to tax evasion.
And, as there was somewhat a return to calm, and as we thought, that UBS would come out of it, there followed this unfortunate story of title dealers: a single title dealer flames 1, 7 billion euros, before the bank realized that something was wrong.
And we publish: with risk management in investment banking, it still doesn&#39;t seem to work.
“With the Adoboli case, we have seen that risk management has changed too little,” says Martin Janssen, economist and professor of finance at the Banking Institute of the University of Zurich.
Also the financial director of a large German bank is sure: &quot;the problem of UBS is that it does not have control of the risks in hand.&quot;
However, it was exactly the idea of prudence, with which the Swiss bankers had long since assumed their function, that of becoming guardians of the great fortune of the world: not too great risks, but security for the money - and the world might well collapse beyond the Alpine republic.
The treasures of the Swiss banks had become the symbol of an unshakable reliability as Lindt and Sprüngli are for a particularly noble chocolate.
The UBS headquarters in Zurich still goes with the solid cliché of the private Swiss bank - it&#39;s only a little bigger.
Already the situation is classic.
The Bank is headquartered at Zurich Central Station, which leads directly from Central Station to Lake Zurich, which itself is surrounded by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are prestigious, the rents for shops are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers like Tiffany&#39;s can be found here among the traditional Swiss shops, as are those of the Sprüngli confectionery.
For centuries Swiss bankers have resided here: from the national bank to the palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks like Julius Bär.
You arrive in the entrance hall of UBS through a heavy door.
Inside, the walls are clad in marble, in front are thick leather chairs, and next to the bank&#39;s logo, a large label for &quot;safe.&quot;
UBS knows what clients are looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has one day or another driven out of the market - or betrayed the two big Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He would prefer not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two big banks.
UBS would have become far too big, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons would have moreover spread.
The Swiss would have nothing more to say about it.
&quot;And even so, they have long since adapted to the mores of the Anglo-Saxons.&quot;
It was indeed the Anglo-Saxon investment bank that changed UBS, it made high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost so much money in the sub-prime jungle like the big Swiss bank.
The disaster became apparent on October 15, 2008.
“On Wednesday the government coalition of the small country of seven million people undertook the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation,” writes author Lukas Hässig in his book “The Crash of UBS”.
With up to around 68 billion francs, or 45 billion euros, the politicians agreed to save the big bank from bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If we speak with Swiss bankers, they see the problem above all in the size of UBS.
In June 1998 two of the three big Swiss banks concluded together a huge group.
A bank was founded, which was already too big for small Switzerland - and has steadily grown.
What helped was that the two different predecessor banks of UBS supplemented: a rich, but lethargic bank with a strong asset management in Zurich and a poorer, but admittedly already more strongly internationalized bank. .
Suddenly, international investment banks had favorable access to a lot of money, with which they were able to spin a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with the rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, from 2001 to 2007 Head of the UBS group, and Marcel Ospel, former chairman of the board of directors.
&quot;I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team,&quot; says bank researcher Hans Geiger.
“Wuffli, the modest, tall intellectual, who is very good at models and statistics, and Ospel, the intuitive, who worked his way to the top with his apprenticeship in banking.”
But Ospel would have trusted Wuffli until the end.
And wuffli would probably have made a decisive mistake in the end: &quot;He thought his models were reality&quot;, says Geiger.
&quot;It&#39;s a tragic fall.&quot;
Tragic, perhaps.
One thing is clear: the exuberance came before the downfall.
UBS staff clearly remember the meetings of the leaders during which the head of the Wuffli group always uttered the same slogan: to dethrone Goldman Sachs.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank on the planet.
She commissioned the &quot;League Tables&quot; rankings, which at that time documented the success of Banks.
After all, UBS wanted to go all the way up.
Some steps have already worked for him.
In matters of currency and securities transactions it has played a very important role.
The corporate advisers, who had the responsibility, pointed out a weakness, however: in international interest transactions, in the banking jargon &quot;Fixed Income&quot;, there would be a huge difference compared to the largest banks.
UBS would have gaps in US mortgage products.
To fill this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure, which almost cost him his life.
Thirsty for growth, it is both the bank itself and a management fund created before it in American sub-prime investments that have invested.
It morphed into a massive machine that packaged and smuggled valuable documents based on US mortgages – but also retained risk.
Even when other banks had long sought to descend.
“Still in the summer of 2007, when the US housing market was in flames, UBS bought there,” says Geiger, the banking expert.
The greater the euphoria, the more brutal the fall.
One manager after another had to leave, when putting an end to the attempts turned out to be more difficult than expected.
Positions at UBS have become ejectable and are so far wobbly.
Whoever runs the big bank has an almost impossible task.
He has to come up with a strategy for a bank, for which all suggested business models have disappeared.
Bank researcher Geiger already has an idea: end investment banking, focus on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
But the bank does not (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking must atrophy vigorously, as far as is clear so far.
Next Thursday bank chief Sergio Ermotti wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Swiss-Italian was only supposed to be on a transitional basis when the bank surprisingly parted ways with his predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has established himself: he must sustainably manage the affairs of UBS, the Bank of Zurich communicated on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to bring investment banking back to where it was in the mid-1990s.
It cancels 3500 jobs.
