Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to his coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, no one who has lived through history will ever forget the media circus President Bill Clinton started by lying in his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
Accounts of cheating on school and college tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers gave test answers to students in order to look good on their performance reviews.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we encounter?
On any given day, studies show you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are white lies.
Another study showed that strangers lie to each other three times within the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone should acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game akin to, say, charades, where the objective is to shout out, &quot;I got you&quot;, deception detection is a serious branch of science-based knowledge. collected over the past six decades from prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research of such projects, particularly in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don&#39;t always stutter, blush or fidget.
Do not conclude that liars are hard to detect and hard to unmask.
A trained lie detector can uncover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years reviewing scientific findings in the vast and still emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are adept at reading others well, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively sensing how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more &quot;self-focused&quot; lies while women tell more &quot;other-focused&quot; lies - usually to protect someone&#39;s feelings. one - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are seen as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty for lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called &quot;establishing benchmarks&quot;.
This helps provide a benchmark against which to measure subsequent changes.
Observe your subject&#39;s posture, laughter, vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally wiggles their feet all the time so you don&#39;t make unfair accusations when you see them wiggling their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and non-verbal deceptive behavior.
Treat these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Cheating people may immobilize their upper body when trying to remember their story, they may point their feet out the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit &quot;post-interview&quot; relief. - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change in posture when all the difficult questions are over.
Interviewers often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to your subject&#39;s vocabulary.
The notorious Scott Peterson went off the rails using the past while pretending his murdered wife was alive, sparking a nationwide search to find her.
Deceptive individuals may also use distanced language: &quot;I haven&#39;t had sex with this woman...Miss Lewinsky&quot; or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of &quot;wooden language&quot; when answering a difficult question: &quot;Well...to tell the truth...if I remember correctly...to my knowledge.&quot;
This makes the answer perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for lie detection, but developing the skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone&#39;s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
