Climate adversity has dampened the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez&#39;s management, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment fell and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it was the first year of Government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled of change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
Low temperatures in February, aside from causing losses of trillions for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state&#39;s economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historical decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the frost damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582 million 835 cultivated hectares were damaged, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the rest 21. 07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the unemployment rate of the state during the first three quarters of the year an accelerated increase was observed, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate became 5.28 percent and from July to September the average continued to rise up to 6.19 percent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand unemployed Sinaloans, an increase compared to the first semester of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
&quot;What we observe is an increase in unemployment which is due to various factors, among which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering. money, because for people who earn dollars in an illicit way, it&#39;s not easy for them to work to earn them, to invest them and use them in something,&quot; he said.
Detained Migration
López Cervantes pointed out that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
&quot;The number of people who leave the state to work abroad in the United States has been limited, first because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because when entering they already have a lot of difficulty finding of work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work there, which causes unemployment to rise,&quot; he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloan labor market is aggravated by considering the high level of lack of seriousness that prevails among the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in this state works there without contributing as worker at any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of seriousness, another reason for the lag for the state is the low salaries, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Forecasting.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which stands at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the IED of the State reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent regarding the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars registered in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat of Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17.280 billion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, in July the State Government requested from the public congress the approval of a credit of 3 billion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the objective of reactivating the economy, the approval of the state congress was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November no benefit of indebtedness was observed in any sector of the economy of the state.
reactions
For the representatives of the business sector, the first year of government of Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the State Government.
&quot;The performance of Sinaloa&#39;s economy during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground we have lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have had to align the efforts of all and above all the already synchronized good progress of this new team of Government, let&#39;s hope that next year will be much better&quot;, he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events like the frosts at the start of the year held back the state&#39;s economy and restricted its performance and growth.
&quot;The low economic flow is the product of several events, among which the frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn quickly enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore at the end of the year we are closing much below the expectations we had,&quot; he said.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers&#39; Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa declared that one wants to channel the State towards productive activities of more dynamism.
&quot;In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and the economic direction of the State, because it is important that we detonates the full potential of Sinaloa&#39;s material and human resources,&quot; he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex underlined the importance of establishing a vision of the future which better channels the Government&#39;s efforts.
&quot;In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term program&quot;, declared- he.
He pointed out that the current administration has shown advances in the way of managing public policy.
&quot;There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have worked a lot and the Government is aware that there is still a lot to do&quot; , he said.
