Quinteto has included the country in its tour to celebrate two decades of trajectory
&quot;Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true&quot;
In the exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready for one of their best shows next Sunday at National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to perform in this country.
That&#39;s what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The band is on the South American wing of its two-decade celebration tour, and Sunday the 20th will make its only stop in Central America.
That day will present themselves at the National Stadium, from 7:30 p.m., next to the group from Los Angeles The X and the Nationals from Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For its Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will perform in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are going through?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I&#39;ve only been to Costa Rica once on vacation; it is such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So it moves us to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion towards the group, the fans live with intensity the previous days.
What is your message for your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took 21 years for us to arrive in Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to pass until this concert.
Some people are already saying that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does add a bit of pressure to your visit.
Some of the biggest shows we&#39;ve offered in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We gave a gigantic two shows in Sao Paolo and hopefully that got us in shape for this show in Costa Rica.
We are really, really looking forward to performing there.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have lots of surfer friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends always went to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that&#39;s how we learned it, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you have given huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never performed there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to do the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What should this be?
I think it&#39;s partly because we have nine records and we can perform over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, that&#39;s why it&#39;s very difficult to choose which songs to perform each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven&#39;t performed for a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and that we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe how much you have achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don&#39;t think any of us imagined that we were going to form a great rock band, and the fact that we&#39;ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and to be able to continue making music together is very emotional for us.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn&#39;t be better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group of great groups.
We are great friends with the folks at Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It&#39;s surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
Once in a while, a band pops out of a town, but it&#39;s much weirder when five or ten bands pop out of the same town at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we&#39;re lucky to still be friends with all of them and it&#39;s an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It&#39;s also very strange that a band like yours stays united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that&#39;s a lot longer than a lot of bands normally last.
First, I believe we are all lucky to still be alive, and second, we all care about each other.
We are all close friends and because of that there are musical avenues that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other&#39;s music and it couldn&#39;t get any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don&#39;t spend too much time on tour because it&#39;s easy to fall into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
If we don&#39;t forget that people are there for the music, it helps us not to forget that we have to respect the music and what brought it, without getting into the head of the fact that we is famous and a rock star, which none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn&#39;t release a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration for the fact that it lasted so little and the most important thing is the fact that we are still very good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us and when i listen to a song or i see a picture i think about the amazing person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to work, laugh, talk about music, football and a lot other things with him.
He was an amazing human being and we miss him.
National group Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder and for that you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with different proposals and that was the group that we liked the most, so we can&#39;t wait to see what Las Robertas can offer live and it must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yello Ledbetter live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don&#39;t know.
He&#39;s the one who sings it and I think he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bassist, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Among the first ones I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, CJ Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam keep grunge alive despite the fact that it&#39;s out of fashion?
I think we all feel a bit disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time and, if it&#39;s relevant now, I think that&#39;s wonderful, because it is music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making the best music ever.
At first his music had more obscure content and now it has become more positive.
What is this change due to?
It&#39;s interesting, because I believe there are songs in the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that qualify as very obscure songs, even though those may sound a bit positive.
With both, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and those are deeply obscure songs.
I think if you grow up and there&#39;s trauma in your life and you lose to a relative or friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
I also think that we can also be happy and even that way we can make dark music.
