Mujica travels to Mexico to consolidate political ties
An official procession, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and made up of various ministers and bosses, will initiate a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highest point in a long agenda of meetings with political and commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans residing in Mexico, according to the agenda released by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara, will be &quot;conducive for the exchange of information in political affairs between the two nations&quot;, according to the information published by the Presidency of the South American country on its web page.
According to local media, Mujica is trying to convince Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that took place when French proxy Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on the list of tax havens in the meeting. of the G20 in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude countries that continue to be tax havens from the international community, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultations from its ambassador from this European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20, a group formed by the strongest emerging and developed countries in the world, since November, and has in force with the South American country, since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to hurry the implementation of tax exchange agreements to get out of the &quot;gri list&quot; of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), included by countries that do not implement all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
On the commercial level, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Treaty (TLC) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
