MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the &#39;Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity&#39; protocol, which will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Investigation and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population with or without the right is invited to participate, to come to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the tests for minors are carried out every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8 the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation is to know the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent obesity. onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As November 14 will be celebrated as World Diabetes Day, he mentioned that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires relating to food.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family heredity of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays all participants will be given anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (the aim is to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
&#39;The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 reported that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity and in the case of girls of 47 percent; as far as overweight is concerned, a dramatic increase has also been observed&#39;, underlined the IMSS specialist.
He said the rationale for searching for the markers is based on the fact that the country&#39;s population is different from others in its genetic history.
He informed that, on average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African ancestry, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the integral evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they present a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed in a confidential way, the doctors give it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measures and changes in the lifestyle that they must carry out to prevent illnesses.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the greater consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - corn flour meat pie wrapped in corn husks -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
The asphalt of the UNAM would avoid the cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher from the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the reports that the cobblestone were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair around 200 thousand currants each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM , who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, blackcurrants could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on blackcurrants, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places in which the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the yield, and therefore the formation of currants.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a collection of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give to the cobblestone its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees C it presents an almost solid state. , while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in their majority were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the layer of asphalt, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it generating forces, it allows the forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, these would spread better, thought the chemical engineer.
On the layer of asphalt, he says, we put a last layer called wearing course, made of fine stone, that is to say, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the wearing course also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material of which it is made must be careful.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these greatly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the ground gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer and it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes blackcurrants.
In the process of formation of a currant, he says, the first thing that gets spoiled is the rolling film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be attended to at the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Researchers System explained that the vehicle load is another important factor for the formation of currants and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the vehicle load and guarantee its satisfaction, for avoid the frequent formation of currants.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow currants to be repaired easily and without having to use high temperatures.
