So was the work of the person from Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A Cali fingerprinter has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of &#39;Alfonso Cano&#39;.
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4, a CTI dactyloscopist from Cali went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;, by comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprinters who work in the local offices of the CTI, this week it was the turn of &quot;availability&quot; of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has worked for 21 years in the field of forensic investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the corpses were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after having taken adequate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of the skin of friction, that is to say the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar had been warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big awaited him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who led the oldest guerrillas in the world, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the place of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant from the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But fingerprints don&#39;t lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a sampler and a lantern, Eliazar compared the corpse&#39;s fingerprints with those on the card.
His eye did not deceive him: it was &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;.
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the person in charge who confirmed to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the Farc.
In search of the footprint
For a fingerprinter from Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against &quot;Cano&quot;, is very significant.
A lot of people don&#39;t know our work.
Fingerprinting is an exact science with no margin for error that can be crucial in solving crimes.
Aside from identifying dead bodies, fingerprinters support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of those captured.
When caught, many offenders present false identity cards or have no documents.
We take their fingerprints and look them up in the database.
The researcher told that in a case of robbery he had to remove part of the wall of a house, because in this place the thief had leaned his hand to extract a safe full of jewels and money.
&quot;The walls are difficult because they are not of adequate surface to take a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to obtain the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in different thefts&quot;, recalls -he.
Fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently a man was found dead, with drink bottles around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a parent may be a suspect in the crime and indeed a print on the bottle matched.
While this doesn&#39;t guarantee he&#39;s the killer, it puts him at the scene of the crime.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that &quot;fingerprints of objects are extracted with chemical or physical reagents&quot;.
When they appear, a sampler or strip is used to collect them.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the declines database, or to the National Civil Registry.
&quot;The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians,&quot; said the CTI expert.
He explained that not everything is how it is shown in the CSI television program.
As all that glitters is not gold, everything you touch does not necessarily become an imprint.
It can however be used, if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
