Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March the Japanese economy had been paralyzed, still convalescing after the devastating earthquake which became a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster for the Japanese country since the Second World War.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo calculated the material losses at 300,000 million dollars, a blow which, despite the difficult global context, seems to have diminished.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to turn the page definitively: the GDP rose by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at an annualized rate.
That recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - supposes, in addition, the greatest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% drop in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulus for the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse which invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructures, to use the deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan woke up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable rose 1%, driven by higher spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
