Tokyo went back to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the &quot;safe havens&quot; chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the uncertain forecasts of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of the big technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed their weak results between July and September on the contribution of the yen.
While the markets continue their sieges in the peripheral countries of the EU, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda does not lower its guard.
“We must monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of certain foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa said yesterday.
And indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) reported that the majority of member countries showed clearer signs of an economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates inflection points in the global economy highlighted that the main powers are being held back.
Because it fell four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even below the average, which is in the 100 level, n dropping eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
