Energy policy:
facts must trump dogma
If there is one subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is healthy for an electoral meeting to be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place nuclear power plays in them.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
With 7 billion people on the planet, demographic change will cause electricity demand to double by 2050 unless we deprive a huge part of the world&#39;s population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to compensate for the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity permanently, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight against climate change, a subject that has disappeared. of the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not modify any of these parameters.
This is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just intends to build only the latest generation plants.
Conversely, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few , pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, they decided after Fukushima to add a unit to their fleet by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the accident at Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality thwarts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, particularly from Russia, a jump in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal.
In a few months, all of these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is worth pondering.
European champion of wind power, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; by virtue of which, its emissions of CO2 and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill that is 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the beautiful declarations on the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show any opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show.
It should be remembered that our country&#39;s energy policy has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Highly exporting, it involves a galaxy of specialized SMEs on international markets and makes them very creative of jobs that cannot be relocated.
If France were to decide to get out of nuclear power, it would be to sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing to a trickle the 6 billion euros of annual French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to operate for sixty years while the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, one must admit that there is no such thing as a miracle power source, any more than there is a diabolical one.
The development by Areva of solutions with low CO2 emissions, nuclear and renewable, testifies to the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a Safety Authority which exercises intransigent and transparent control over existing power plants and the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human fault caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident resulted from two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude which caused the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the two previous ones.
The result of this approach and cooperation between the French and German safety authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR has a design that makes it capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians wishing to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to the competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them the way to seize leadership in the unavoidable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogma and partisan maneuvers dominate a debate that is so decisive for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy conducted under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - overcrowding of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of numbers, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of &quot;country of human rights &quot; from France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment to which foreign students are subject that has made the news, the Minister of the Interior (see Liberation of May 23) proclaiming in passing that France &quot;does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant waiters&quot;.
But it is only rarely analyzed from an economic angle.
There is a fairly broad consensus between left and right on this subject.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that &quot;900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers&quot;, and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France &quot; cannot accommodate all the misery in the world&quot; in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left as on the right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference lies in the degree of generosity that we deign to grant to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will make it possible to solve our &quot;migration problem&quot;.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may pay off electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book summarizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.) , there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migratory flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration stunts growth and hurts jobs.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they risk replacing national workers, especially the low-skilled, putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly working in jobs in sectors with job shortages.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not keep pace with the job offer.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anaesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that the arrival of immigrants has a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals. .
Giovanni Peri has thus calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real wages in the long term.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and to economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo have were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average up to 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labor Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of €150,000 to public budgets on average over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the start of his term, to pick up the missing growth points &quot;with his teeth&quot;.
The teeth in question, by serving to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, we still have to think about European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember it, which, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would suffice, for democracy to definitively triumph over its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon &quot;the Little&quot;, that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, while being the necessary condition of democracy, is not its sufficient condition and can even become an “instrument of oppression” as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and above all a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinodie of the true-false Greek referendum will have had in this respect the double value of revealing: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought out in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the Democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them the Republican soldiers are no longer pulling in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to need and in scattered order.
A blank check to the absolute European monarch or a jump with both feet into the void of nationalist withdrawal: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we don&#39;t want cleavers but a joint, full, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, in Italy, in Spain, in Portugal - we would not know where to stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that bows to the diktats of the markets and the rating agencies, that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe which is humiliated on the international scene.
We are worried about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the piloting of the European project.
Because it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level which cannot be taken without total democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After having long fought this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic government.
Either.
But to think so without a stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by the citizens, would be a new folly and a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage in European construction.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to &quot;make&quot; republicans.
The Revolution in the interests could not be enough there.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic Europe, genuine European popular sovereignty.
To make Europe, let&#39;s make Europeans.
&quot;Contactless&quot; smart cards are becoming widespread
The world smart card fair opens Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, in an optimistic climate.
The year 2011 should indeed end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank card, telephone with SIM card, etc.), to more than 6 billion units, according to Eurosmart.
The most buoyant segment is that of contactless technology, which makes it possible to pay for public transport or pay for purchases by simply tapping the card against a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless smart cards should be sold worldwide, compared to 320 million a year earlier!
Their share should increase further in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent almost 10% of the global smart card market (6.925 million cards).
Long lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region, Europe is gaining ground in contactless payment.
Some 26 million Visa bank cards are already equipped with this functionality and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa contactless cards have been deployed.
But the supermarkets are working twice as hard.
Carrefour thus issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass cards this year.
To move up a gear, banks now need to equip their customers.
“Two major French establishments have undertaken to systematically distribute contactless-equipped bank cards to their customers in the future,” announces Gérard Nébouy, Managing Director of Visa Europe France.
Banks test mobile payment
But this is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Few devices today are equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is essential for carrying out transactions.
&quot;They&#39;ve fallen behind.&quot;
&quot;But they should finally see a real boom next year.&quot;
&quot;We are counting on the sale of 80 to 120 million units in 2012 worldwide&quot;, explains Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the lead.
Crédit Agricole yesterday announced the launch of a test from December to June in Caen.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees will be equipped with a case allowing contactless payment.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale, too, said yesterday that it was preparing to market an offer allowing its customers to pay without contact with their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front extends
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaida in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Suspected for a long time, the links between the terrorist group al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram are confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Messahel, even affirmed that Algiers has now &quot;acquired certainty&quot;.
“The way the two organizations operate and the reports from the intelligence services show that there is cooperation,” he explained without further details.
Paris seems to make a similar analysis.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have brought to light bridges.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by relatives of Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day along with several of their captors during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, the French and Nigerien investigators had to find several telephone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of the calls made directs towards several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers are of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who spent a long time in Maiduguri, a town in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who says he is close to Aqmi and the sect.
&quot;It&#39;s a step forward but we should probably wait for more formal proof before talking about operational cooperation between AQMI and Boko Haram&quot;.
&quot;But it is possible&quot;.
&quot;We have known for years that the sect benefits from external financial and intellectual support and that it is becoming more and more active&quot;, tempers Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, this &quot;support&quot; had been increasingly evident in the development and discourse of Boko Haram or in its operating methods, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or increasingly complex explosive devices and same invoice as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore put pressure on Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have indeed long considered the group as a community of enlightened little worthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means in Hausa &quot;Western education is a sin&quot; - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this impoverished region, the association enjoyed rapid success.
It becomes politicized and demands strict adherence to Sharia law while its activists take up the fight against the impious central government.
The latter are primarily aimed at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active, stepping up attacks on police stations.
Abuja&#39;s reaction is, as usual, without nuances.
The army invests the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
From then on, the sect will radicalize and leave its strongholds in the north.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for an attack that killed 80 people in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, it was again in Abuja that Boko Haram attacked the secure police headquarters in a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the local United Nations headquarters will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia via Nigeria now worries all security specialists.
While AQIM has taken over Mali and Niger, while the Somalis of al-Chebab are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram is emerging as a new threat at the heart of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready &quot;to share all the information&quot;.
The World According to Republican Presidential Candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete in simplicity and ignorance.
Can an America weakened by the crisis manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe him.
For the past few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the others have been multiplying thunderous declarations and shortcuts in matters of foreign policy, traditionally a strong Republican point.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, the slogans - often unsubstantiated - fuse.
Mitt Romney, the best placed in the race for the nomination of the &quot;Grand Old Party&quot;, threatened to drag the Chinese before the WTO and to blame them &quot;for manipulation of their currency&quot;, a theme carrying in an exasperated America by the migration of whole sections of its industry to Asia.
Too bad if that means starting a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama&#39;s ex-ambassador to China and the only candidate with a sophisticated foreign policy vision, nearly choked on an attitude that &quot;flattered&quot; the emotions.
He called for a tough but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama&#39;s current position).
But Huntsman, who is languishing in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
Like Reagan
Romney has also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
&quot;If elected, I will stop Iran,&quot; he boasted.
&quot;If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb.&quot;
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing in his obligations vis-à-vis this partner.
The entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best-placed candidate, displays an embarrassing lack of knowledge of the files.
Recently he called for countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing is “trying to develop a nuclear capability” – apparently unaware that China has had the military atom since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants strikes against Iran, says he is ready to engage the US military in Mexico against drug cartels.
The use of torture against suspected terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
We are far from the Republican candidate of 2008, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president counter that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They remind us that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to water down his wine when it came to anti-terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, on the too hasty departure of the &quot;boys&quot; from Iraq, on his procrastination in Libya, thus labeling him as weak.
But the attack is not so easy.
The population considers the national security record of Obama, who eliminated bin Laden, to be rather positive.
From Iraq, she is wary of military interventions that lead to stagnation.
And, by arguing that America must be rebuilt economically to resurrect its leadership, Obama strikes more accurately.
The Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe directly to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a bang.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part, last Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic, between an orchestra and a fine buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline which directly connects, under the sea , Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte together turned the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the West European network. .
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first 1,224 km tube linking the region of Saint Petersburg to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed at the end of 2012, making it possible to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, ie the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same course.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project looks like a victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will indeed make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a &quot;new German-Soviet pact&quot;, in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is to say if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But this is at the cost of a weakening of energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in barely five years, to bring about the triumph of its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavy consumers of gas and whose deposits are in decline.
&quot;This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically&quot;, confirmed François Fillon in inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent major gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in large numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-encased steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal serpent, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, uninterrupted over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but those responsible for the project abandoned it when the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state company permanently established off their coast.
&quot;In the event of damage, we stop the flow of gas in less than a minute,&quot; says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders who have planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the gas pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, towed by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter wide in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it delivers precise information on any deformations in the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which retains 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF joined it (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty years renewable, all of the gas transport capacity.
&quot;Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the quantity of gas actually transported&quot;, specifies Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to recover their costs, since only Gazprom bears the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy shore lined with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
Sensors measure the pressure, the temperature and the specificities of the incoming gas, before it is transferred into the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to give back the taste of writing.
It smells of adventure, of hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves in an off-white color, as if aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (mole skin) which designates a varnished cotton used to cover benches for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
&quot;Moleskine has brought up to date an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century&quot;, says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to reach 12.7 million pieces sold.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Difficult to establish a composite portrait of the buyer, because the notebook seduces the businessman as well as the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees when it started, has almost 100 today and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small downtown shops and has managed to impose her identity.
&quot;We followed the spirit of the times and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails&quot;, explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched a &quot;Detour&quot; exhibition where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard print cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, diary, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a whole range of supports.
A success that made people envious: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was taken over by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for workers with disabilities still so high?
Around 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy implemented in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
&quot;No, underlines Éric Blanchet, general manager of Adapt, the association which organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.&quot;
“The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable.”
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher.”
&quot;However, there is still a lot to do.&quot;
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before accessing employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the bac and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, against 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria which singularly complicate the return to employment, and which &quot;constitute the crux of the problem&quot;, according to Christian Grapin, general manager of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
There remains the unsaid, the mentalities which evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association indicated that the managers questioned have &quot;a low level of knowledge of disability&quot;, with an &quot;over-representation of people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled people&quot;.
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% disabled workers, set in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, which date from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
&quot;We are now around 3%,&quot; says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of “taxed” establishments, just like the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
&quot;The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies, explains Pierre Blanc.&quot;
&quot;But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups.&quot;
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
