Portugal very confident
Paulo Bento&#39;s Portugal begins its comeback play-off against Bosnia (10:00 p.m.) with great optimism, this Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, the two teams lacked realism.
&quot;At the end of these 90 minutes, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country&quot;.
Paulo Bento already sees himself there, in Poland and Ukraine.
For him, there is no shadow of a doubt, the Selecçao, which he has been at the helm since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Portugal is actually only 90 minutes away from happiness.
But there is a game to play, and an adversary, Bosnia, to unbolt.
In view of the first leg (0-0), Friday in the hell of Zenica, it seems obvious that the games are not made.
Portugal dominated the game for more than an hour, of course, but they were unable to score this precious goal, which would have relieved them.
&quot;It&#39;s a good result, but it does come with some risk because we didn&#39;t score an away goal.&quot;
But at home, in their bright Stade de la Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced to pass, in front of an audience which should be there as hot, even if the game obviously looks &quot;very tight&quot;, according to an optimistic but lucid Bento .
&quot;We are expecting a very tight game, but we are completely confident that we can get the upper hand,&quot; said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
&quot;We continue to have a 50% chance of being at Euro 2012&quot;, nevertheless relativized Carlos Queiroz&#39;s successor.
The draw reported Friday from Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
A draw may be enough for the Bosnians, who also need to score.
&quot;It&#39;s a good result, which however involves a certain risk because we didn&#39;t score an away goal&quot;, regrets Bento.
&quot;We are going to play against a team which has a lot of technical qualities and which has players with a lot of individual qualities,&quot; he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will intend to put maximum pressure on the Bosnians from the start in order not to &quot;give them time to think.&quot;
A good idea, provided you are realistic this time.
